<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-250-012 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 754 283</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  Jan 1991 v14 n1 p55(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A love/hate relationship: suuuurvey SAYS... despite the down side,users want graphics standards. (a survey by the National ComputerGraphics Association) (includes a related article on thestandards-testing process)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cramblitt, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A recent survey by the National Computer Graphics Association(NCGA) of 343 attendees of the association's Integrate '90demonstration (chosen randomly) finds that resistance to graphicsstandards continues among users and vendors alike, although bothgroups realize the eventual benefits of standardization.andP;  Vendorswant to maximize profits from proprietary systems, retain productdifferentiation and avoid the time and expense of adoptingstandards; users balk at the time required to implement standards,the lack of standards-based products and poor standardsimplementations from vendors.andP;  Forty-five percent of the surveyrespondents are involved in CAD/CAM or architectural applications,and 38 percent use business graphics; 77 percent say buyingstandards-based products is important to their organizations, and29 percent of this group say it is a requirement.andP;  Other surveyresults are examined.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SurveyComputer GraphicsStandardizationTrade and Professional AssociationsUser NeedsHardware VendorsSoftware PublishersIndustry AnalysisNational Computer Graphics Association.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Standards currently in use. (graph)Importance of purchasing standards-based products. (graph)Problems with products not conforming to standards? (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>